    <!-- Begin page content -->
    <div class="container">
      <div class="page-header">
        <h1>The question</h1>
      </div>
      <p class="lead"><br><br>
It could be a bar that sells alcoholic beverages or any other business, the important issue we want to prove with this website is that data science can provide value and insight for all size of problems, and that it should not be regarded as an exclusive domain of big technological companies.<br><br>
In this site, we use publicly available information from the US Census Bureau in combination with a Random Forest model, to provide information about the market for bars, or <i>7224: Drinking places (alcoholic beverages)</i> for their technical denomination, on a county basis. Based on the local population, the number of travelers (included through the number of hotels), and the area of the county, this very simple model can evaluate whether a particular county has the right number of bars, to few or too many.<br><br>
The information generated by this model is presented in two different ways, both accessible through the menu on the top of the page. The first option is a county-specific, short market analysis result presented after selecting a US state and county from the drop-down menus of the <b>Pick a county</b> section. The second alternative is to access the charts with the rankings of the 20 best and worst counties to open a bar, available by clicking on the <b>Rankings</b> menu option.  
<br><br><br><b>Note:</b> This entire website is part of a capstone project for the Galvanize Data Science Immersive program. As such, it should be considered a "proof of concept" or "prototype" product that demonstrates some of the capabilities unleashed by the field of Data Science and not as a definitive business advise.</div>




